I stopped in to Dunkin Donuts for coffee, and had to wait a bit. The coronavirus and social distancing have made things like that difficult, due to  the limiting of the number of people who can be inside the store at one time. I absolutely get that, however, the scene behind the counter was a bit chaotic. I'm not sure if they are training new employees, but the manager was called from the back to assist. She was a big help and easily remedied the issues. Every business has chaotic times. I'm not holding that against them. Every employer must train new employees. They were apologetic for my wait, and my coffee was spot-on and delicious. I truly believe this was an anomaly to their typical service quality, so I'm giving them decent marks. If I had to make one change, I would suggest  increased employee training and employee "shadowing." before sending noobs to fly solo behind the counter. Other than the wait, and the little bit of confusion about the order of the customer in front of me, they did a great job.

What became of Dunkin Doughnuts? Back in 74 when I was teenager I worked at a Dunkin Doughnuts. Half the back wall was all doughnuts, fresh made all day and night, by hand, by real live people I know because I made them myself. Today you go into a DD and there are a few racks of Doughnuts to pick from and they are trucked in from a central kitchen, meaning who the h e double hockey sticks knows where or how old they are. And now they really took a swim in the toilet by offering them at your every other corner 2-5 (sorry they don't deserve a 7-11 rating. So sad when a winning product has a terrible press agent. Bring back the good old way when kids pressed their noses against the glass watching the Doughnuts being made.
